| url          = https://archive.org/details/janesarmourartil0000unse
| url-access   = registration
| location     = London
| publisher    = IHS Global Limited
| pages        = 879–881
| isbn         = 978-0-7106-2960-9
}}</ref>

In February 2022, the French government awarded Nexter a contract for the development of a new generation CAESAR system. Marketed by the company as the '''CAESAR Mark II''' (also commonly referred to as '''CAESAR NG''' in France), 109 systems are to be delivered to the French Army between 2026 and 2030.

==Development==
In the early 1990s, the French Army operated two artillery systems designed and manufactured by the state-owned company GIAT: the [[AMX-30 AuF1|AuF1]] tracked self-propelled howitzer, which had reached the end of its production run, and the [[TRF1]] towed howitzer, which was beginning to be delivered, but in reduced numbers. Absent further orders for its products, GIAT might have had to shut down its artillery program for unprofitability, permanently losing an important industrial capability. Since the French Ministry of Defence had expressed no interest in acquiring or funding new artillery designs at the time, the firm had to use its own funds to develop a {{cvt|155|mm}} system that could attract export customers.<ref name="caia-girard">{{cite magazine |last=Girard |first=Philippe |date=28 March 2023 |title=Le CAESAR, ou la genèse atypique d'un matériel d'armement |trans-title=The CAESAR, or the unusual genesis of a weapon system |url=https://www.caia.net/revue-auteurs-rubriques-numeros/article/le-caesar-ou-la-genese-atypique-d-un-materiel-d-armement/1191 |language=fr |magazine=Le magazine des ingénieurs de l'armement |location=Paris |publisher=[[:fr:Corps des ingénieurs de l'armement|Confédération Amicale des Ingénieurs de l'Armement]] |access-date = 20 June 2024}}</ref>

Per the then-emerging NATO standard, the new design would need a 52-caliber barrel, which would offer greater accuracy and longer range than the 39-caliber barrels on GIAT's existing models. For strategic mobility, the system would have to be air-transportable on a [[Lockheed C-130 Hercules|C-130]] along with an entire gun crew and 18 rounds of ammunition. Using the TRF1 and its usual tow vehicle, the [[Renault TRM 10000]], as a baseline, the project team determined that mounting the gun directly on a truck bed would reduce overall material costs. After designing a subframe and a rear anchoring platform to filter and dissipate the gun's [[recoil]], the team chose to adapt the Unimog U2450 truck as the system's base. In cooperation with Unimog importer [[Lohr Industrie]] (now Soframe), which supplied the cab and helped design the interface between the truck and the subframe, GIAT produced the first prototype in less than a year and displayed it at the [[Eurosatory]] defence industry fair in June 1994.<ref name="janes-foss" /><ref name="caia-girard" />

Four years later, a second pre-production model underwent trials with the French Army in 1998 and the [[Malaysian Army]] in 1999. Based on this early performance, the {{lang|fr|[[Ministry of Armed Forces (France)#DGA|Direction Générale de l'Armement]]}} (DGA) ordered five additional prototypes for further testing in September 2000. After delivery was completed in June 2003, the French Army formed an "experimental" artillery section that used the prototypes to develop [[military doctrine]] for future CAESAR-equipped units. The findings convinced the French Army to order more CAESARs instead of continuing to upgrade its AuF1 self-propelled howitzers to the AuF2 standard. Thus, in December 2004, the DGA awarded GIAT a €300 million contract to produce 72 new CAESARs, upgrade the five vehicles already delivered, supply an initial amount of ammunition, and provide maintenance to the fleet for five years. The new systems would have a new purpose-built truck chassis, the Sherpa 5 by [[Renault Trucks Defense|Renault Trucks Defence]] (RTD), instead of the Unimog-Soframe chassis of the prototypes.<ref name="janes-foss" /><ref name="giatmag-april2001">{{cite magazine |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=April 2001 |title=Caesar à l'honneur |trans-title=Caesar in the spotlight |url=http://www.giat-industries.fr/giat/actu/img/giatmag.pdf |url-status=dead |language=fr |magazine=GIAT Magazine |location=Paris |publisher=GIAT Industries |page=4 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20010305103449fw_/http://www.giat-industries.fr/giat/actu/img/giatmag.pdf |archive-date=5 March 2001 |access-date=22 June 2024}}</ref><ref>{{cite press release |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=20 September 2000 |title=Commande de canons CAESAR à Giat Industries |trans-title=Order for Caesar howitzers from Giat Industries |url=http://www.giat-industries.fr/giat/actu/actu33.htm |url-status=dead |language=fr |location=Paris |publisher=Délégation à l’Information et à la Communication de la Défense |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20010611014440/http://www.giat-industries.fr/giat/actu/actu33.htm |archive-date=11 June 2001 |access-date=22 June 2024}}</ref><ref>{{cite press release |author= <!--Not stated--> |date= 24 June 2003 |title=Delivery of Caesar artillery systems to the French Army |url=http://www.giat-industries.fr/asp/us/acccommu_detail.asp?id=60 |url-status=dead |location=Versailles-Satory, France |publisher= GIAT Industries |website= giat-industries.fr |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20030802094702/http://www.giat-industries.fr/asp/us/acccommu_detail.asp?id=60 |archive-date=2 August 2003 |access-date=21 June 2024}}</ref><ref>{{cite press release |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=13 December 2004 |title=La France commande 72 canons d'artillerie Caesar® à Giat Industries |trans-title=France orders 72 Caesar artillery cannons from Giat Industries |url=http://www.giat-industries.fr/asp/fr/acccommu_detail.asp?id=82 |url-status=dead |language=fr |location=Versailles-Satory, France |publisher=GIAT Industries |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050119191936/http://www.giat-industries.fr/asp/fr/acccommu_detail.asp?id=82 |archive-date = 19 January 2005 |access-date=21 June 2024}}</ref>

In 2006, the year that the company was reorganised and renamed to Nexter, GIAT received the first export orders for the CAESAR, from the [[Royal Thai Army]] (RTD chassis) and the [[Saudi Arabian National Guard]] (Unimog-Soframe chassis).<ref>{{cite press release |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=3 April 2006 |title=First export contract for CAESAR artillery systems |url=http://www.giat-industries.fr/asp/us/acccommu_detail.asp?id=98 |url-status=dead |location=Versailles-Satory, France |publisher=GIAT Industries |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060616033851/http://www.giat-industries.fr/asp/us/acccommu_detail.asp?id=98 |archive-date=16 June 2006 |access-date=21 June 2024}}</ref><ref>{{cite press release |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=20 July 2006 |title=CAESAR® artillery systems go on with export success |url=http://www.giat-industries.fr/Communique_Pdf/CaesarExport-GB.pdf |url-status=dead |location=Versailles-Satory, France |website= giat-industries.fr |publisher=GIAT Industries |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20061129155752/http://www.giat-industries.fr/Communique_Pdf/CaesarExport-GB.pdf |archive-date=29 November 2006 |access-date=21 June 2024}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ttu.fr/francais/Dossiers/idex2007.html |title=IDEX 2007: Premiers enseignements |author=<!--Not stated--> |editor-last=Perrimond |editor-first=Guy |date=February 2007 |website=TTU Online |series=Dossiers |publisher=Certes SARL |language=fr |trans-title=IDEX 2007: First lessons |access-date=2024-07-14 |url-status=dead |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20071016094918/http://www.ttu.fr/francais/Dossiers/idex2007.html |archive-date=2007-10-16 |quote=Les succès du Caesar à l’exportation, avec le contrat conclu avec l’armée de terre thaïlandaise (six Caesar/RTD) et la Garde nationale saoudienne (76 Caesar), devraient lui ouvrir les portes des autres pays du Golfe (Koweït, Oman, Qatar et EAU), qui ont déjà manifesté leur intérêt. |trans-quote=The success of the Caesar in exports, with the contract concluded with the Thai army (six Caesar/RTD) and the Saudi National Guard (76 Caesar), should open the doors of other Gulf countries (Kuwait, Oman, Qatar and the UAE) who have already expressed interest.}}</ref> Well before the French, Thai, or Saudi orders were completely fulfilled, the French Army began to use the CAESAR in combat, [[French forces in Afghanistan|deploying]] eight systems to [[War in Afghanistan (2001–2021)|Afghanistan]] in 2009.<ref name="janes-foss" />

