=== CAESAR 6×6 Mark I ===
The CAESAR is a wheeled, 155&nbsp;mm [[Caliber (artillery)|52-caliber]] [[Self-propelled artillery|self-propelled]] [[howitzer]]. It holds 18 rounds and is typically operated by a crew of five, though if necessary the CAESAR can be operated by a crew of three.<ref name="nexter brochure">{{cite web |author=<!--not stated--> |date=June 2018 |title=CAESAR® 6x6: Deployed in combat operations since 2009 |type=Brochure |publisher=[[Nexter Systems]] |url=https://www.knds.fr//sites/default/files/fichiers-catalogue-produit/CAESAR%206X6_2.pdf |access-date=16 July 2024}}</ref> It can be transported by a [[C-130]] or an [[A400M]] aircraft. It has a firing range of approximately {{convert|42|km|mi}} using an [[Extended range full bore|Extended Range, Full Bore]] (ERFB) shell,<ref>{{Cite conference |url=https://asat.journals.ekb.eg/article_25665_987e8a5fd08bf4dd1b97a1fcd8a2c2fd.pdf |title=Assessment of ERFB-BB Projectile |first1=Hassan |last1=Yakout |first2=Mohamed S.|last2=Abdel-Kader |publisher=Military Technical College |location=Cairo |date=14–16 May 1991 |conference=Fourth ASAT Conference |id=MF-366}}</ref>{{irrelevant citation|date=July 2024|reason=Source does not mention CAESAR at all}} and more than {{convert|50|km|mi}} using rocket-assisted shells.{{citation needed|date=July 2024}} The CAESAR has an autonomous weapon system featuring an [[inertial navigation system]] (the [[SIGMA 30]]), a ballistic computer and an optional muzzle velocity radar; the system is adaptable to any [[C4I]] system (fully integrated with the ATLAS [[Fire Control System|FCS]]). At Eurosatory 2016, the CAESAR was exhibited with an automated laying system based on the SIGMA 30.<ref>{{Cite press release |author=<!--not stated--> |date=14 June 2016 |title=Safran dévoile à Eurosatory 2016 sa nouvelle gamme de centrales d'artillerie Sigma 30 |url=https://www.safran-group.com/fr/espace-presse/safran-devoile-eurosatory-2016-sa-nouvelle-gamme-centrales-dartillerie-sigma-30-2016-06-14 |language=fr |publisher=[[Safran]] |trans-title=Safran unveils its new line of Sigma 30 artillery control units at Eurosatory 2016 |access-date=16 July 2024}}</ref> Tailored for [[shoot-and-scoot]] tactics, the CAESAR is fast to set up, taking around 60 seconds for the crew to be ready to fire and 40 seconds to leave after the shots. It can fire six rounds per minute.<ref name="nexter brochure" /><ref name="mt" />

=== CAESAR 8×8 ===
The CAESAR 8×8 uses a modified [[Tatra 817]] 8x8 chassis, allowing a higher degree of mobility.<ref>{{Cite magazine |last=Kominek |first=Jiri |date=24 March 2017 |url=http://www.janes.com/article/68983/denmark-orders-caesar-howitzers-on-8x8-tatra-trucks |title=Denmark orders CAESAR howitzers on 8x8 Tatra trucks |magazine=[[Jane's Defence Weekly]] |publisher= Janes Information Services |access-date=12 October 2017 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20171013013823/http://www.janes.com/article/68983/denmark-orders-caesar-howitzers-on-8x8-tatra-trucks |archive-date=13 October 2017 |url-status=dead}}</ref> It is fitted with an unarmoured forward control four-person cabin as standard, with an optional fully-armoured cabin. Gross vehicle weight would depend on the level of armour protection but is about 30 tonnes. It is powered by a 410&nbsp;hp diesel engine<ref>{{Cite web |last= Foss |first=Christopher F. |date=16 September 2015 |url=http://www.janes.com/article/54396/caesar-rolls-in-on-eight-wheels-dsei15-d2 |title=Caesar rolls in on eight wheels [DSEI15, D2] |website=[[Janes Information Services|Janes]] |access-date=8 February 2016 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20160309193823/http://www.janes.com/article/54396/caesar-rolls-in-on-eight-wheels-dsei15-d2 |archive-date=9 March 2016 |url-status= dead}}</ref> and can hold 36 rounds.<ref>{{cite web |author=<!--not stated--> |date=June 2018 |url= https://www.knds.fr/sites/default/files/fichiers-catalogue-produit/CAESAR%208X8_2.pdf |title=CAESAR® 8X8: The future of a revolutionary concept |website= knds.fr |publisher=[[Nexter Systems]] |type=Brochure |access-date=16 July 2024}}</ref> It was unveiled by Nexter at [[DSEI]] 2015.

=== CAESAR 6×6 Mark II ===
[[File:CAESAR_NG_(Mk._II)_New_Generation_155mm_6x6_self-propelled_howitzer.png#/media/File:CAESAR_NG_(Mk._II)_New_Generation_155mm_6x6_self-propelled_howitzer.png|thumb|CAESAR NG|link=File:CAESAR_NG_(Mk._II)_New_Generation_155mm_6x6_self-propelled_howitzer.png]]
In February 2022, Nexter was awarded an initial €600 million contract by the French defence procurement agency (the [[Direction générale de l'armement|DGA]]) for the development and acquisition of the CAESAR 6×6 Mark II new generation artillery system.<ref>{{cite press release |author=<!--not stated--> |date=24 February 2022 |title=Une commande de 1,8 milliard d'euros pour des canons et véhicules de nouvelle génération |url=https://www.defense.gouv.fr/actualites/commande-18-milliard-deuros-canons-vehicules-nouvelle-generation |language=fr |publisher=[[Ministry of Armed Forces (France)|Ministry of Armed Forces]] |trans-title=A €1.8 billion order for next-generation cannons and vehicles |access-date=16 July 2024}}</ref> The deal initiated a four-year development phase, after which the ''CAESAR Mark II'' (or ''CAESAR NG'') is planned to enter production. In January 2024, the DGA announced that it had awarded Nexter an additional €350 million contract on 30 December 2023. 109 CAESAR NG systems are to be produced for the French Army.<ref name="defensenews.com">{{cite web |last=Ruitenberg |first=Rudy |date=2 February 2024 |title=France orders €1.1 billion of cannons, vehicles and helicopters |url=https://www.defensenews.com/global/europe/2024/02/02/france-orders-11-billion-of-cannons-vehicles-and-helicopters/ |website=[[Defense News]] |publisher=[[Sightline Media Group]] |access-date=16 July 2024}}</ref><ref name="forcesoperations.com">{{cite web |last=Gain |first=Nathan |date=2 February 2024 |title=109 CAESAR neufs pour entamer un nouveau chapitre de l'artillerie française |url=https://www.forcesoperations.com/109-caesar-neufs-pour-entamer-un-nouveau-chapitre-de-lartillerie-francaise/ |website=Forces Operations Blog |language=fr |trans-title=109 new CAESARs to begin a new chapter in French artillery |access-date=16 July 2024}}</ref> Nexter, the industrial prime contractor, will be working in particular with [[Renault Trucks#Military vehicles|Arquus]] (chassis) and [[Safran]] (electronics), the main partners involved in the development and implementation of this program.<ref>{{cite press release |author=<!--not stated--> |date=1 February 2024 |title=La Direction générale de l'armement a commandé 109 canons Caesar de nouvelle génération (Mk II) |url=https://dicod.hosting.augure.com/Augure_Dicod/r/ContenuEnLigne/Download?id=90F4C2B0-BC1E-433E-9BDD-FE7F0F53B281&filename=Communiqu%C3%A9_%20La%20Direction%20g%C3%A9n%C3%A9rale%20de%20l%E2%80%99armement%20a%20command%C3%A9%20109%20Canons%20Caesar%20de%20nouvelle%20g%C3%A9n%C3%A9ration%20%28Mk%20II%29.pdf |language=fr |publisher=[[Ministry of Armed Forces (France)|Ministère des Armées]] |trans-title=The Directorate-General of Armaments has ordered 109 next-generation Caesar cannons (Mk II) |access-date=16 July 2024}}</ref>

From mobility to connectivity, and from ballistic protection to increased firing efficiency, as well as accuracy further refined by an [[artificial intelligence]] system developed by [[Helsing (company)|Helsing]],<ref>{{cite web |last=Lagneau |first=Laurent |date=24 January 2024 |title=Artillerie : Helsing IA va rendre le CAESAr encore plus efficace grâce à l'intelligence artificielle |url=https://www.opex360.com/2024/01/24/artillerie-helsing-ia-va-rendre-le-caesar-encore-plus-efficace-grace-a-lintelligence-artificielle/ |language=fr |website=Zone Militaire |trans-title=Artillery: Helsing AI will make CAESAr even more efficient thanks to artificial intelligence |access-date=16 July 2024}}</ref> the improvements remain those set out in 2022 when the program was launched.<ref name="forcesoperations.com"/> The CAESAR Mark II will feature a new six-wheel chassis provided by ''Arquus'', a new cabin with improved armor and, this time, four doors for improved agility.<ref name="forcesoperations.com"/> The system will also feature a new 460&nbsp;hp engine, more than twice as powerful as the previous one (215&nbsp;hp), as well as a new automatic gearbox. It will incorporate a new version of its velocity radar and new fire control software, as well as Safran's ''Geonyx'' inertial navigation system to replace the SIGMA 30, which promises enhanced geolocation and pointing accuracy in environments with no [[GNSS]] signal. Another differentiating feature is a more powerful hydraulic pump, enabling the stabiliser to be lowered and raised more quickly. This development could, in theory, shave a few precious seconds off engagement and disengagement maneuvers.<ref name="forcesoperations.com"/> Finally, the cabin will be predisposed to receive the [[vetronics]] of the ''SCORPION'' combat information network, such as the NCT-t (noeud de communication tactique - terre) software radio from the CONTACT program and the ECLIPSE anti-[[improvised explosive device|IED]] jammer from [[Thales Group|Thales]], a technology that could be extended to anti-drone warfare, and which [[Belgium]] has chosen to integrate natively.<ref name="forcesoperations.com"/> The new armored cabin to protect against mines and [[STANAG 4569#Level 2|ballistic projectiles]] is expected to raise the CAESAR Mark II's weight to 25 tonnes (27.56 tons) but the system will remain [[A400M|air-transportable]], an indispensable French requirement.<ref name="defensenews.com"/>

All 109 units ordered for the French Army are expected to be delivered between 2026 and 2030.<ref name="defensenews.com"/> Belgium and [[Lithuania]] are the first export customers of the new system and have respectively ordered 28 and 48 units.<ref name="forcesoperations.com"/><ref name="litf24">{{cite news |author=<!--not stated--> |date=14 June 2022 |title=Lithuania to buy howitzers from France |url=https://www.france24.com/en/live-news/20220614-lithuania-to-buy-howitzers-from-france |agency=[[Agence France-Presse]] |via=[[France24]] |access-date=16 July 2024}}</ref>

==Operational deployment==
[[File:Caesar 6.jpg|thumb|Ukrainian artillerymen using a French-supplied CAESAR during the [[Russo-Ukrainian War]]]]
Eight CAESARs were sent to Afghanistan during the summer of 2009 to support French operations. They were deployed on 1 August 2009 by the [[3rd Marine Artillery Regiment]] ({{lang|fr|3è RAMa}}), followed by five others, deployed as a firebase in FOB Tora, Tagab and Nijrab. They were fitted with cabin armor add-ons, with fireports.<ref name="Blog Secret Defense">{{cite web |url=http://secretdefense.blogs.liberation.fr/defense/2009/06/la-france-va-envoyer-des-canons-caesar-en-afghanistan.html |title=La France va envoyer huit canons CAESAR en Afghanistan |trans-title=France will send eight CAESAR cannons to Afghanistan |last=Merchet |first=Jean-Dominique |date=29 June 2009 |website=Secret Défense |publisher=[[Libération]] |language=fr |access-date=27 June 2024 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090701063054/http://secretdefense.blogs.liberation.fr/defense/2009/06/la-france-va-envoyer-des-canons-caesar-en-afghanistan.html |archive-date=1 July 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite press release |author=<!--Not stated--> |title=Afghanistan : arrivée des CAESAR |trans-title=Afghanistan: arrival of the CAESARs |url=https://archives.defense.gouv.fr/operations/missions-realisees/monde/operation-pamir-2001-2014/actualites/03-08-09-afghanistan-arrivee-des-caesar-video.html |language=fr |location=Paris |publisher=[[Ministry of Armed Forces (France)|Ministère de la Défense]] |date=3 August 2009 |access-date=27 June 2024}}</ref>

The French Army deployed this system in southern Lebanon as part of the [[United Nations Interim Force in Lebanon|UNIFIL]] peacekeeping force.{{fact|date=May 2026}}

During [[Operation Serval]] in Mali, four CAESARs were deployed by the {{lang|fr|68<sup>e</sup> régiment d'artillerie d'Afrique}} (68th African Artillery Regiment).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://forcesoperations.com/2013/01/17/mali-vbci-caesar-engages-dans-loperation-serval/ |title=Mali: VBCI et Caesar engagés dans l'opération Serval |trans-title=Mali: VBCI and Caesar engaged in Operation Serval |last=Belan |first=Guillaume |date=17 January 2013 |language=fr |website=Forces Operations Blog |access-date=5 November 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141105172832/http://forcesoperations.com/2013/01/17/mali-vbci-caesar-engages-dans-loperation-serval/ |archive-date=5 November 2014 |url-status=dead}}</ref>

In April 2011, the [[Royal Thai Army]] used the CAESAR against Cambodia's [[BM-21 Grad|BM-21]]. The Thai Army claimed that they destroyed two or more BM-21 systems.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://rpdefense.over-blog.com/artillery-caesar-gets-bulletproof-just-in-case|title=Artillery : Caesar Gets Bulletproof, Just In Case|work=RP Defense|access-date=5 November 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141106040541/http://rpdefense.over-blog.com/artillery-caesar-gets-bulletproof-just-in-case|archive-date=6 November 2014|url-status=live}}</ref>

Several CAESARs were deployed in Mali by France during [[Operation Serval]], in which they saw action in the [[Battle of Ifoghas]], amongst others. France also deployed four CAESARs to Iraq for the [[Battle of Mosul (2016–17)|Battle of Mosul]], where French forces supported the Iraqi Army's operation to reclaim [[Mosul]] from ISIS from October 2016 to July 2017.<ref>{{cite news |author= <!--Not stated--> |title=Mossoul : le Charles de Gaulle manque le début de l'offensive |trans-title=Mosul: the ''Charles de Gaulle'' misses the start of the offensive |url=http://www.ouest-france.fr/monde/irak/mossoul-le-charles-de-gaulle-manque-le-debut-de-l-offensive-4565591 |access-date=17 October 2016 |work=[[Ouest-France]] |date=17 October 2016 |language=fr-FR |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161020011800/http://www.ouest-france.fr/monde/irak/mossoul-le-charles-de-gaulle-manque-le-debut-de-l-offensive-4565591 |archive-date=20 October 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref> Multiple CAESARs were deployed to Iraq on the Syrian border from 8 November 2018 to April 2019 to support the [[Syrian Democratic Forces]] in the [[Battle of Baghuz Fawqani]], the ultimately successful operation to capture the [[Al-Baghuz Fawqani|final town]] held by the [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant|Islamic State group]]. They were deployed to Firebase Saham, a base freshly constructed by the United States Army to provide fire support during the battle, especially during cloudy days when U.S. aircraft could not see to conduct airstrikes.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.army.mil/article/215289/firebase_saham_a_day_in_the_life_of_joint_artillerymen_securing_the_iraq_border |title=Firebase Saham: A day in the life of joint-artillerymen securing the Iraq border |last=Welch |first=Jason |date=18 December 2018 |website=U.S. Army |language=en-US |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190419021415/https://www.army.mil/article/215289/firebase_saham_a_day_in_the_life_of_joint_artillerymen_securing_the_iraq_border |archive-date=19 April 2019 |url-status=live |access-date=19 April 2019}}</ref>

CAESAR howitzers may have been used by the Saudi Arabia National Guard during the [[Saudi Arabian–led intervention in Yemen|Saudi-led intervention in Yemen]] along the Saudi-Yemeni frontier, conducting defensive shelling of Houthi forces as well as backing up Yemeni government troops and Saudi armed forces in their progression into Yemeni territory.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-yemen-security-france-arms-idUSKCN1RR1D3 |title=French-made tanks and howitzer canons used in Yemeni war: Disclose |date=15 April 2019 |work=Reuters |access-date=16 May 2019 |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190512122405/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-yemen-security-france-arms-idUSKCN1RR1D3 |archive-date=12 May 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>

France provided the CAESAR 6×6 cannon to Ukraine from May 2022 onwards in the context of the [[Russo-Ukrainian War]],<ref name="auto">{{Cite news |last=Macron |first=Emmanuel |subject-link=Emmanuel Macron |interviewer1= Michael Backfisch |interviewer2= Céline Bardy |interviewer3= Gaëlle Fleitour |interviewer4= Laurent Marchand |interviewer5= Stefano Montefiori |date=22 April 2022 |title= Le risque d'escalade en Ukraine est très fort |trans-title= The risk of escalation in Ukraine is very high |url=https://www.ouest-france.fr/politique/emmanuel-macron/le-risque-d-escalade-en-ukraine-est-tres-fort-d79f638e-c1a5-11ec-8a48-02f9bba22954 |language=fr |work=Ouest-France |access-date=22 April 2022}}</ref> delivering a total of 30 units.<ref>{{cite press release |author=<!--Not stated--> |title= Livraison de nouveaux canons Caesar pour l'armée de Terre |trans-title=Delivery of new Caesar cannons for the Land Army |url= https://www.defense.gouv.fr/terre/actualites/livraison-nouveaux-canons-caesar-larmee-terre |language=fr |location=Paris |publisher=[[Ministry of Armed Forces (France)|Ministère de la Défense]] |date=7 December 2023 |access-date=28 June 2024}}</ref><ref name="Reuters">{{cite news |last1=Rose |first1=Michel |last2= Vidalon |first2=Dominique |last3=Polityuk |first3=Pavel |title=France to send 12 additional Caesar cannons to Ukraine| url= https://www.reuters.com/world/europe/france-send-12-additional-caesar-howitzers-ukraine-2023-01-31/ |editor1-last=Sithole-Matarise |editor1-first=Emelia |date=31 January 2023 | work=Reuters |access-date=28 June 2024}}</ref> Denmark also announced that it had delivered all 19 of its CAESAR 8×8 howitzers to Ukraine by the end of April 2023.<ref name="air-cosmos.com">{{Cite magazine |last=Powis |first=Gaétan |date=28 April 2023 |title=Les CAESAr danois sont déployés en Ukraine |trans-title=The Danish CAESARs are deployed in Ukraine |url=https://air-cosmos.com/article/les-caesar-danois-sont-deployes-en-ukraine-64891 |language=fr |magazine=[[Air & Cosmos]] |location=Paris |publisher=Discom S.A.S. |access-date=1 May 2023}}</ref> As of February 2025, 7 CAESARs were confirmed to have been destroyed (6 CAESAR 6×6 and 1 CAESAR 8×8) and a further 3 damaged.<ref>{{cite news |last=Grynszpan |first=Emmanuel |date=14 December 2023 |title=Dans le Donbass, les soldats ukrainiens en panne de munitions |trans-title=In the Donbas, Ukrainian soldiers are running out of ammunition |url=https://www.lemonde.fr/international/article/2023/12/14/dans-le-donbass-les-soldats-ukrainiens-en-panne-de-munitions_6205755_3210.html |language=fr |work=[[Le Monde]] |location=Paris |access-date=28 June 2024}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last1=Mitzer |first1=Stijn |last2=Oliemans |first2=Joost |last3=Janovsky |first3=Jakub |title=Attack On Europe: Documenting Ukrainian Equipment Losses During The Russian Invasion Of Ukraine |url=https://www.oryxspioenkop.com/2022/02/attack-on-europe-documenting-ukrainian.html |access-date=25 June 2023 |website=Oryx}}</ref>

