<!--READ FIRST: This section is for cited entries only. Please do not add entries into this list without a citation from a reliable source. All entries without a citation will be removed. Thank you.-->

===Current operators===

*{{flagicon|Armenia}} - [[Armenian Armed Forces]]: Alongside the [[Eurosatory]] 2024 Exhibition, the Defence Ministry of Armenia and the [[KNDS]] defence company signed a military-technical agreement. A day later, the French defence minister Sébastien Lecornu announced the signing of a contract with Armenia for the acquisition of CAESAR Mk1 cannons. With the sale to Croatia and Estonia, the total reached 60 systems, meaning 36 for Armenia. CAESAR was seen on 11 May 2026 during parade rehearsals.<ref>{{Cite web |last= |date=2024-06-18 |title=Armenia and France Sign Military-Technical Cooperation Agreement |url=https://massispost.com/2024/06/armenia-and-france-sign-military-technical-cooperation-agreement/ |website=MassisPost.com |language=en-US |access-date=2024-06-18}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=Armenian Defense Ministry, French company sign military-technical cooperation agreement |url=https://armenpress.am/en/article/1193891 |website=[[Armenpress]] |date=17 June 2024 |language=en |access-date=2024-06-18}}</ref><ref name=":0" /><ref>{{Cite web |date=2026-05-11 |title=Pashinyan shares sneak peek of May 28 military parade rehearsals |url=https://armenpress.am/en/article/1249836 |access-date=2026-05-11 |website=Armenpress |language=en}}</ref>
*{{flagicon|EST}} - [[Estonian Land Forces]]: On 19 June 2024, Estonia ordered 12 French-made CAESAR Mk1 cannons. The agreement has an option to buy additional units.<ref>{{cite news |date=19 June 2024 |title=Estonia buys Caesar self-propelled cannons from France |url=https://news.err.ee/1609375864/estonia-buys-caesar-self-propelled-howitzers-from-france |access-date=19 June 2024 |work=[[Eesti Rahvusringhääling]] |location=Tallinn, Estonia}}</ref><ref name=":0">{{Cite web |date=2024-06-20 |title=KNDS Caesar cannon is now the most exported European artillery system |url=https://meta-defense.fr/en/2024/06/20/canon-caesar-knds-eurosatory-2024/ |access-date=2024-06-21 |website=meta-defense.fr |language=en}}</ref> The first batch of six units was delivered in January 2025 <ref>{{cite web |title=The Estonian Defence Forces Receive the First Batch of CAESAR Self-Propelled Guns |url=https://www.baltictimes.com/the_estonian_defence_forces_receive_the_first_batch_of_caesar_self-propelled_howitzers/ |website=The Baltic Times |access-date=30 January 2025 |date=30 January 2025}}</ref> Last year, the Estonian Defence Forces received the first 12 CAESAR MK1 155-millimeter self-propelled howitzers.<ref>https://news.err.ee/1609939514/estonia-to-procure-another-12-caesar-self-propelled-howitzers</ref> Additional 12 units were procured in early 2026, bringing the total number to 24 by year's end.<ref>[https://debuglies.com/2026/02/16/estonias-caesar-expansion-and-renewed-france-estonia-defence-cooperation-sovereign-security-financial-forensics-2026/ Estonia’s CAESAR Expansion and Renewed France–Estonia Defence Cooperation — Sovereign Security & Financial Forensics 2026.]</ref>
*{{flagicon|France}} - [[French Army]]: The first order (for 5 cannons) was placed on 20 September 2000. The first five units were delivered in 2003. Following the evaluation, the main order of 72 CAESAR 6×6 cannons was made in late 2004. In July 2008, the first cannon of the first batch of eight units was delivered to the [[French Army]].<ref>{{cite press release| last= Daffix| first= Bruno| title= La DGA livre le premier canon CAESAR à l'armée de terre| url= http://www.defense.gouv.fr/dga/votre_espace/presse/communiques/2008/la_dga_livre_le_premier_canon_caesar_a_l_armee_de_terre| location= Paris| publisher= [[Direction générale de l'armement]]| access-date  = 26 July 2008| archive-url  = https://web.archive.org/web/20080725230347/http://www.defense.gouv.fr/dga/votre_espace/presse/communiques/2008/la_dga_livre_le_premier_canon_caesar_a_l_armee_de_terre| archive-date = 25 July 2008}}</ref>
*{{flagicon|Indonesia}} - [[Indonesian Army]]: The Indonesian Army acquired 37 CAESAR units for $240 million, the first two arriving in mid-September 2012. Another 18 were purchased in a follow-up order signed in February 2017.<ref>{{cite news| last= Cabirol| first= Michel| date= 18 September 2012| title= Défense : quand le Danemark veut du 'Made in France'| url= http://www.latribune.fr/entreprises-finance/industrie/aeronautique-defense/20120918trib000720087/defense-quand-le-danemark-est-seduit-par-le-made-in-france.html| work= La Tribune| location= Paris| access-date= 5 November 2014| archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20141105173432/http://www.latribune.fr/entreprises-finance/industrie/aeronautique-defense/20120918trib000720087/defense-quand-le-danemark-est-seduit-par-le-made-in-france.html| archive-date = 5 November 2014| url-status= live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Tomkins|first1=Richard|title=Nexter providing CAESAR gun systems to Indonesia|url=http://www.upi.com/Defense-News/2017/02/20/Nexter-providing-CAESAR-howitzer-systems-to-Indonesia/1051487606754/|website= upi.com| publisher= [[United Press International]] |archive-url= https://archive.today/20170221123719/http://www.upi.com/Defense-News/2017/02/20/Nexter-providing-CAESAR-howitzer-systems-to-Indonesia/1051487606754/ |archive-date=21 February 2017|date=20 February 2017|url-status=dead |access-date=21 February 2017}}</ref>
*{{flagicon|Morocco}} - [[Royal Moroccan Army]]: In January 2020, Morocco agreed to purchase CAESAR 6×6 howitzers, at a total cost of €170 million for the artillery pieces and €30 million for the ammunition.<ref>{{cite news| last= Cabirol| first= Michel| date= 21 January 2020| title= Armement : le Maroc achète un peu de "Made in France" mais énormément de "Made in USA"| url= https://www.latribune.fr/entreprises-finance/industrie/aeronautique-defense/armement-le-maroc-achete-un-peu-de-made-in-france-mais-enormement-de-made-in-usa-837558.html| url-status= live| work= La Tribune| location= Paris| archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200626222933/https://www.latribune.fr/entreprises-finance/industrie/aeronautique-defense/armement-le-maroc-achete-un-peu-de-made-in-france-mais-enormement-de-made-in-usa-837558.html| archive-date = 26 June 2020| access-date  = 4 July 2020}}</ref> In early September 2022, the Royal Moroccan Artillery received 36 of up to 60 systems available to order under this contract.<ref>{{cite news| last= Jnina| first= Zaira| date= 3 September 2022| title= Morocco receives French Caesar artillery systems after long delay| url= https://en.hespress.com/48645-morocco-receives-french-caesar-artillery-systems-after-long-delay.html| work = [[Hespress]]| location= Rabat, Morocco| access-date = 20 June 2024}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news| last= El Kanabi| first= Mohamed Jaouad| date= 24 December 2022| title= Maroc-armement : Les raisons du choix de l'obusier Caesar| url= https://fr.hespress.com/295255-armement-les-raisons-du-choix-de-lobusier-caesar.html| language= fr| work= Hespress| location= Rabat, Morocco| access-date = 20 June 2024| quote= Le Royaume a acquis 36 pièces d’artillerie françaises Caesar avec l’option d’atteindre les 60 dans un futur proche, et ce, dans le cadre d’un accord signé en début d’année 2020 d’une valeur d’environ 170 millions d’euros auxquels s’ajoutent 30 autres pour les munitions.}}</ref><ref>{{Cite report| author= | date = July 2023| title= Rapport au Parlement 2023 sur les exportations d'armement de la France| url= https://www.defense.gouv.fr/sites/default/files/ministere-armees/Rapport%20au%20Parlement%202023%20sur%20les%20exportations%20d%E2%80%99armement%20de%20la%20France%20(07%202023).pdf| publisher= [[:fr:Délégation à l'information et à la communication de la Défense]], Ministry of Armed Forces| page= 113| access-date= 20 June 2024}}</ref>
*{{flagicon|Saudi Arabia}} - [[Saudi Arabian National Guard]]: In 2006, GIAT announced a 76-unit sale plus a 4-unit option to an unspecified foreign customer, later confirmed to be [[Saudi Arabia]].<ref name="Libération">{{cite news| last= Merchet| first= Jean-Dominique| date= 20 July 2006| title= Des canons français pour l'Arabie saoudite| url= http://www.liberation.fr/actualite/economie/194547.FR.php| url-status= dead| language= fr| work= [[Libération]].fr | location= Paris| archive-url  = https://web.archive.org/web/20060721193533/http://liberation.fr/actualite/economie/194547.FR.php| archive-date= 21 July 2006| access-date= 20 June 2024}}</ref> The 4 optional units became firm sales in January 2007, with the first two units to be assembled in France and the other 78 in Saudi Arabia.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.janes.com/events/exhibitions/eurosatory2008/sections/french/daytwo/dj-163-feuilles-de-laurie.shtml |title=Déjà 163 'feuilles' de laurier à la couronne de Caesar |last=De Lestapis |first=Jacques |date=17 June 2008 |website=Janes.com| publisher= Janes Information Services |language=fr |access-date=22 July 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090801050236/http://www.janes.com/events/exhibitions/eurosatory2008/sections/french/daytwo/dj-163-feuilles-de-laurie.shtml |archive-date=1 August 2009 |url-status=dead}}</ref> In March 2010, the Saudi Arabian National Guard (SANG) was delivered its first four units.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.janes.com/news/defence/jdw/jdw100331_2_n.shtml |title=Saudi Arabia takes delivery of first CAESARs |last=Barreira |first=Victor |date=31 March 2010 |website= Janes.com| publisher= Janes Information Services |access-date=22 July 2024 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100408230542/http://www.janes.com/news/defence/jdw/jdw100331_2_n.shtml |archive-date=8 April 2010}}</ref> All 80 units were delivered by 2018.
*{{flagicon|Thailand}} - [[Royal Thai Army]]: 6 CAESAR mounted on Sherpa 6×6 truck chassis were ordered in 2006 and have been operated by the Royal Thai Army (RTA) since 2010.<ref name="DF" /><ref name="Libération" />
*{{flagicon|Ukraine}} - [[Ukrainian Ground Forces]]: In response to the [[2022 Russian invasion of Ukraine]], France and Denmark provided Ukraine with several CAESAR guns. As of October 2025, KNDS France reports that 120 CAESAR Mk1 (6×6 and 8×8) systems are currently deployed in Ukraine.<ref>{{Cite press release |date=13 October 2025 |title=Leonardo DRS and KNDS Sign Strategic Teaming Agreement to Offer High-Performance Self-Propelled Howitzer to U.S. Army |url= https://investors.leonardodrs.com/news-releases/news-release-details/leonardo-drs-and-knds-sign-strategic-teaming-agreement-offer| website= leonardodrs.com| publisher= | access-date= }}</ref>
