===Future deliveries===
*{{flagicon|Belgium}} - [[Belgian Army]]: Following the acquisition of the [[VBMR Griffon|Griffon]] and [[EBRC Jaguar|Jaguar]] within the CaMo-program, Belgium decided in 2021 to order 9 CAESAR NG 6×6 cannons in a contract of approximately €48 million. In June 2022 a €62 million contract was signed for an additional 19 CAESAR NG. Delivery of the first units is expected in 2027.<ref>{{Cite web| url= https://businessam.be/na-de-controverse-over-de-aankoop-van-de-f-35-kiest-het-belgisch-leger-ditmaal-voor-een-nieuw-frans-kanon| title= Na de controverse over de aankoop van de F-35, kiest het Belgisch leger ditmaal voor een nieuw Frans kanon| date= 3 November 2021| website= BusinessAM.be| language= nl| trans-title= After the controversy surrounding the purchase of the F-35, the Belgian army has now opted for a new French gun| access-date= 2025-11-12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Lagneau |first=Laurent |date=30 June 2022 |title=Artillerie : La Belgique va commander 19 CAESAr de nouvelle génération supplémentaires à la France |url= http://www.opex360.com/2022/06/30/artillerie-la-belgique-va-commander-19-caesar-de-nouvelle-generation-supplementaires-a-la-france/ |website= opex360.com| publisher= Zone Militaire |language=fr-FR |access-date=27 July 2022}}</ref>
*{{flagicon|Croatia}} - [[Croatian Army]]: Framework agreement signed at Eurosatory 2024 with France, without an obligation to purchase it in the Mk2 variant.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2024-06-21 |title=Croatia and France sign framework agreement for joint procurement of CAESAR howitzers |url=https://defence-industry.eu/croatia-and-france-sign-framework-agreement-for-joint-procurement-of-caesar-howitzers/ |access-date=2024-06-21 |language=en}}</ref><ref name=":0" /> Budget approved for the purchase of 18 systems in October 2025.<ref>{{Cite web |date=5 November 2025 |title=Croatia to launch €1.9 billion defence upgrade to boost army strength and NATO interoperability |url=https://defence-industry.eu/croatia-to-launch-e1-9-billion-defence-upgrade-to-boost-army-strength-and-nato-interoperability/}}</ref> The contract was signed in December 2025.
*{{flagicon|Czech Republic}} - [[Czech Land Forces]]: In June 2020, Nexter won a €200 million contract to provide the CAESAR 8×8 to the Czech Army. 52 systems integrated on the Czech Tatra 815–7T3RC1 8×8 chassis were ordered.<ref>{{Cite web| url= https://www.armadninoviny.cz/houfnice-caesar-pro-armadu-ceske-republiky.html| title= Houfnice CAESAR pro Armádu České republiky| website= Armádní noviny| language= cs| access-date  = 6 June 2020| archive-date = 28 June 2020| archive-url  = https://web.archive.org/web/20200628045840/https://www.armadninoviny.cz/houfnice-caesar-pro-armadu-ceske-republiky.html| url-status = dead}}</ref> 10 additional units were ordered in December 2022.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.idnes.cz/zpravy/domaci/ministerstvo-obrany-armada-nakup-houfnice-caesar.A221216_110111_domaci_tbr | title=Česko reaguje na napětí ve světě. Přikoupí další houfnice Caesar za 1,77 miliardy| website= idnes.cz| publisher= | date=16 December 2022 | language=cs| access-date= }}</ref>
*{{flagicon|France}} - [[French Army]]: 109 CAESAR NG are on order for the French Army and will be delivered from 2026 onwards.<ref>{{Cite web |date=10 July 2023 |title=PROJET DE LOI relatif à la programmation militaire pour les années 2024 à 2030 et portant diverses dispositions intéressant la défense |url= https://www.assemblee-nationale.fr/dyn/16/textes/l16b1517_texte-adopte-commission.pdf | language = fr| website= assemblee-nationale.fr| trans-title= DRAFT LAW relating to military planning for the years 2024 to 2030 and containing various provisions concerning defense | access-date= 2025-11-12}}</ref>
*{{flagicon|Lithuania}} - [[Lithuanian Land Forces]]: In June 2022 Lithuania joined the CAESAR NG (Mk2) program with an order for 18 units, with first deliveries expected in 2027.<ref>{{cite web|title=La Lituanie a l'intention d'équiper un bataillon d'artillerie avec des CAESAr acquis auprès de Nexter|access-date=13 June 2022|date=13 June 2022|url= http://www.opex360.com/2022/06/13/la-lituanie-a-lintention-dequiper-un-bataillon-dartillerie-avec-des-caesar-acquis-aupres-de-nexter/ |first=Laurent|last=Lagneau|language=fr|publisher=Zone Militaire}}</ref><ref name="litf24"/> On 10 December 2025, Lithuania has signed a contract for a second batch of 30 CAESAR NG (Mk2), which will be delivered by 2030.<ref>{{Cite web |last=SAUVETON |first=Pierre |date=2025-12-11 |title=La Lituanie achète 30 CAESAr Mk II supplémentaires |url=https://opexnews.fr/lituanie-30-caesar-mk2-supplementaires-france/ |access-date=2025-12-11 |website=OpexNews |language=fr-FR}}</ref>
*{{Flagicon|Portugal}} - [[Portuguese Army]]: The new Military Programming Law signed in 2023 provides funds for the acquisition of a 155 mm 8×8 self-propelled artillery system to replace the current [[M114 155 mm howitzer|M114A1 155 mm howitzers]].<ref name=":27">{{Cite web |last= |date=2024-03-14 |title=Portugal's comprehensive equipment modernisation |url=https://euro-sd.com/2024/03/articles/37091/portugals-comprehensive-equipment-modernisation/ |access-date=2024-06-14 |website=euro-sd.com |language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=O 🇵🇹 @exercitoportugues_oficial considera adquirir duas baterias de sistemas auto-propulsados de artilharia de campanha |trans-title=The Portuguese Army is considering acquiring two batteries of self-propelled field artillery systems |url=https://www.instagram.com/accounts/login/?next=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.instagram.com%2Fp%2FCqQuv3ysP1_%2F |access-date=2023-06-07 |website=instagram.com |language=pt}}</ref> It was mentioned on [[CNN Portugal]] that the CAESAR would be the most likely [[cannon]] of this type to equip the Army.<ref name=":30">{{Cite web |title=Gouveia e Melo quer um navio porta-drones mas há mais - o que vai mudar nas Forças Armadas |trans-title=Gouveia e Melo wants a drone carrier ship, but there's more to it — what will change in the Armed Forces? |url=https://cnnportugal.iol.pt/videos/gouveia-e-melo-quer-um-navio-porta-drones-mas-ha-mais-o-que-vai-mudar-nas-forcas-armadas/668eaa2d0cf2a41c2ee0291a |access-date=2024-07-11 |website=cnnportugal.iol.pt |publisher=CNN Portugal |language=pt}}</ref> Portugal confirmed an initial order for two batteries (twelve units) of SPW 155 6×6 growing to a maximum of 36 units. As of November 2025, it is confirmed that the Land Force 2045 programme includes the purchase of 36 CAESAR Mk2<ref>{{Cite web |last=Militar |first=Redaccion Zona |date=2026-01-09 |title=Artilheiros portugueses treinaram na Romênia com o CAESAR, futuro obuseiro autopropulsado do Exército de Portugal |url=https://www.zona-militar.com/pt/2026/01/09/artilheiros-portugueses-treinaram-na-romenia-com-o-caesar-futuro-obuseiro-autopropulsado-do-exercito-de-portugal/ |access-date=2026-01-11 |website=Zona Militar |language=pt-BR}}</ref>, 18 to replace the [[M114 155 mm howitzer|M114A1]] and 18 to replace the [[L118 light gun|M119 LG]].<ref>{{Cite web |date=5 November 2025 |title=Audition of the defence minister |url=https://canal.parlamento.pt/cid/8852/audicao-do-ministro-da-defesa-nacional}}</ref>
*{{flagicon|Slovenia}} - [[Slovenian Army]]: In July 2024, the Slovenian MoD signed a Letter of Intent with the French MoD on the European joint procurement of CAESAR artillery systems.<ref name=":1">{{Cite web |date=2024-07-12 |title=Mors s Francozi podpisal namero o nabavi caesarjev |url=https://www.24ur.com/novice/slovenija/mors-s-francozi-podpisal-namero-o-nabavi-caesarjev.html |access-date=2024-07-16 |language=Slovenian}}</ref><ref name=":0" /> In June 2025, the Ministry of Defence confirmed the order for 12 systems, which will be delivered by 2028. An additional 6 systems will be ordered and delivered by 2030. This will bring the Slovenian Armed Forces to a total of 18 Mk2 systems.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2025-06-13 |title=Ministrstvo za obrambo potrdilo naročilo 12 artilerijskih sistemov Caesar {{!}} GOV.SI |url=https://www.gov.si/novice/2025-06-13-ministrstvo-za-obrambo-potrdilo-narocilo-12-artilerijskih-sistemov-caesar/ |access-date=2025-06-18 |website=Portal GOV.SI |language=sl}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=2025-06-13 |title=Slovenia buys French-made howitzers |url=https://sloveniatimes.com/43831/slovenia-buys-french-made-howitzers |access-date=2025-12-21 |website=sloveniatimes.com |language=en}}</ref>

=== Potential operators ===
* {{flagicon|Brazil}} - [[Brazilian Army]]: On 30 October 2024, the Brazilian media reported that France's President [[Emmanuel Macron]] during his trip to [[Rio de Janeiro]] to participate the [[2024 G20 Rio de Janeiro summit|2024 G20 summit]] will offer to the Brazilian President [[Luiz Inácio Lula da Silva]] a package of armaments, including the 36 CAESAR.<ref>{{Cite news |title=G20: França vai oferecer ao Brasil helicópteros H145M, caças Rafale, obus CAESAR e mais um Submarino? |trans-title=G20: Will France offer Brazil H145M helicopters, Rafale fighters, CAESAR howitzers and another submarine?|url=https://www.defesaaereanaval.com.br/geopolitica/g20-franca-vai-oferecer-ao-brasil-helicopteros-h145m-cacas-rafale-obus-caesar-e-mais-um-submarino|date=31 October 2024|work=Defesa Aérea e Naval|language=pt}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |title=Macron oferecerá 24 caças Rafale a Lula no encontro do G20|trans-title=Macron to offer 24 Rafale fighter jets to Lula during the G20 meeting|url=https://www.aereo.jor.br/2024/10/31/macron-oferecera-24-cacas-rafale-a-lula-no-encontro-do-g20/|date=31 October 2024|work=Poder Aéreo|language=pt}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |title=França vai oferecer 24 caças Rafale ao Brasil, segundo jornalista |trans-title=France will offer 24 Rafale fighter jets to Brazil, according to journalist|url=https://www.airway.com.br/franca-vai-oferecer-24-cacas-rafale-ao-brasil-segundo-jornalista/|date=31 October 2024|work=Airway|language=pt}}</ref> The offer comes as the [[ATMOS 2000]] of [[Elbit Systems]] that was selected in 2024 is with contract signing on hold as a result of diplomatic tensions over the [[Gaza war]] and [[Israel–Hezbollah conflict (2023–present)|Israel–Hezbollah conflict]].<ref>{{Cite web |date=9 October 2024 |title=Segundo Ministro da Defesa, compra do Atmos está parada por causa de questões ideológicas |url=https://www.defesaaereanaval.com.br/exercito/segundo-ministro-da-defesa-compra-do-atmos-esta-parada-por-causa-de-questoes-ideologicas |website=Defesa Aérea e Naval |language=pt}}</ref>
* {{flagicon|Bulgaria}} - [[Bulgarian Land Forces]]: The Bulgarian Minister of Defence, [[Atanas Zapryanov]] confirmed that Bulgaria has intent to join in a joint procurement program for CAESAR artillery systems. Bulgaria plans to purchase 57 systems<ref>{{Cite web |title=Bulgaria wants to buy French howitzers CEASAR - Euractiv |url=https://www.euractiv.com/section/politics/news/bulgaria-wants-to-buy-french-howitzers-ceasar/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20250305084938/https://www.euractiv.com/section/politics/news/bulgaria-wants-to-buy-french-howitzers-ceasar/ |archive-date=5 March 2025 |access-date=2025-03-10 |website= euractiv.com |language=en-GB |url-status=live }}</ref>
* {{flagicon|Finland}} - [[Finnish Navy]]: 12 to 20 mobile artillery systems tender launched to replace the 15 [[130 53 TK|Appellate 130 53 TK]] 130&nbsp;mm for coastal protection mission.The competitors are the Mk2 variant and the [[Archer artillery system|Archer]].<ref>{{Cite web |last=Chała |first=Marcin |date=2024-07-16 |title=Mobilne systemy artyleryjskie dla Merivoimatu |url=https://zbiam.pl/mobilne-systemy-artyleryjskie-dla-merivoimatu/ |access-date=2024-07-19 |website=Wydawnictwo militarne ZBIAM |language=pl-PL}}</ref>
* {{Flagicon|Iraq}} - [[Iraqi Army]]: The Commander of the Iraqi Ground Forces expressed interest to purchase the CAESAR artillery system in 2022. The system had been previously deployed in the country by French troops to support Iraq in key battles against [[Islamic State]].<ref>{{cite web|url= https://defense-arab.com/news/62019/|title= العراق مهتم بشراء مدافع هاوتزر الفرنسية ذات العجلات من طراز سيزار 155 ملم|date=13 February 2022 |publisher=Defense Arab| language= ar| trans-title= Iraq is interested in purchasing French-made Caesar 155mm wheeled howitzers| access-date= }}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url= https://armyrecognition.com/archives/archives-land-defense/land-defense-2022/iraq-shows-interest-to-acquire-french-caesar-155mm-wheeled-self-propelled-howitzers|title=Iraq shows interest to acquire French CAESAR 155mm wheeled self-propelled howitzers|date=12 February 2022 |publisher=Army recognition}}</ref>
* {{flagicon|Malaysia}} - [[Malaysian Army]]: Offered by KNDS in May 2024, and to be assembled and integrated in the industrial facilities of Advanced Defence Systems Sdn. Bhd. (ADSSB) in Segamat.<ref>{{cite press release| author= <!--Not stated-->| title= DSA 2024: KNDS France offers the Caesar 6x6 to meet the needs of the Malaysian artillery units| url= https://www.knds.fr/en/our-news/latest-news/dsa-2024-knds-france-offers-caesar-6x6-meet-needs-malaysian-artillery-units| location= Amsterdam, Netherlands| publisher= [[KNDS]]| date= 6 May 2024| access-date= 19 June 2024
}}</ref>
* {{flagicon|Philippines}} - [[Philippine Army]]: Procurement of additional [[ATMOS 2000]] was initially planned.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://defencesecurityasia.com/en/philippines-to-acquire-additional-12-atmos-155mm-self-propelled-howitzers-from-israel/ |title=Philippines to Acquire Additional 12 ATMOS 155mm Self-Propelled Howitzers from Israel |website=defencesecurityasia.com |date=8 February 2025 |access-date=9 November 2025}}</ref> However, delays on existing defence procurement contracts from Israel that are partly attributable to [[Gaza War]], and Israel’s neutral stance regarding Philippine claims in the [[West Philippine Sea]], have prompted a review of alternative self-propelled howitzers.<ref>{{Cite news |last= Azulay |first= Yuval |date=20 May 2025 |title= Philippines freezes Israeli arms deals over South China Sea standoff |url= https://www.calcalistech.com/ctechnews/article/b1q00h2tblx |work=[[Calcalist]]}}</ref> As a result, the CAESAR and [[152_mm_SpGH_DANA#Variants|DITA]] were shortlisted for potential acquisition.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Elmas |first=Dean Shmuel |date=20 October 2025 |title= Philippines omits Elbit from howitzer tender |url=https://en.globes.co.il/en/article-philippines-omits-elbit-from-howitzer-tender-1001524086 |work=[[Globes (newspaper)|Globes]]}}</ref>

=== Former operators ===
*{{flagicon|Denmark}} - [[Royal Danish Army]]: On 14 March 2017 the CAESAR 8×8 was chosen to become the new artillery system of the [[Royal Danish Army]]. 15 cannons were ordered in May 2017 and an additional 4 in October 2019 for a total of 19 CAESAR units.<ref>{{Cite web| url= http://www.fmn.dk/nyheder/Pages/nyt-materiel-til-forsvaret.aspx| title= Nyt materiel til Forsvaret| website= [[Ministry of Defence (Denmark)|Forsvarministeriet]]| language= da| access-date= 19 June 2024| archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20170315085600/http://www.fmn.dk/nyheder/Pages/nyt-materiel-til-forsvaret.aspx| archive-date= 15 March 2017| url-status= dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Felstead|first1=Peter|title=Nexter announces Danish 8x8 CAESAR contract|url=http://www.janes.com/article/70687|website= Janes.com| publisher= Janes Information Services |access-date=24 May 2017|archive-url= https://archive.today/20170524103225/http://www.janes.com/article/70687/nexter-announces-danish-8x8-caesar-contract|archive-date=24 May 2017|date=23 May 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite press release| author= <!--Not stated-->| title= Denmark orders 4 additional CAESAR® 8X8| url= https://www.knds.fr/en/our-news/latest-news/denmark-orders-4-additional-caesarr-8x8| location= Satory, France| publisher= [[Nexter Systems]]| date= 28 October 2019| access-date= 19 June 2024}}</ref> Delivery of the first 15 units was expected to take place by summer 2020 but the COVID pandemic led to the delivery of a first batch being delayed to spring 2021, with delivery of all 19 units expected in 2023.<ref>{{Cite web |last= |first= |title=COVID-19 delays delivery of Danish Caesar 8×8 artillery systems to 2021 |url=https://defbrief.com/2020/06/23/covid-19-delays-delivery-of-danish-caesar-8x8-artillery-systems-to-2021/ |publisher= Defense Brief |website= defbrief.com|date=2020-06-23 |language=en-US |access-date=2023-04-14}}</ref> However, following discussions with France, Denmark decided on 19 January 2023 to [[List of military aid to Ukraine during the Russo-Ukrainian War|donate all systems to Ukraine]] in the context of the 2022 Russian invasion.<ref name="DR 19Jan2023"/><ref>{{Cite news |date=2022-10-02 |title=France supplies Ukraine with more Caesar howitzers |language=en |work= LeMonde.fr |url= https://www.lemonde.fr/en/international/article/2022/10/02/france-about-to-deliver-more-caesar-guns-to-ukraine_5998801_4.html |access-date=2023-04-14}}</ref> The capability gap that arose from this decision led to a new bid for which Nexter, once again, and [[Israel]]'s [[Soltam Systems]] competed. Denmark opted for the ATMOS 2000 system over the CAESAR, with the production backlog of the CAESAR and Soltam's ability to quickly deliver the howitzers being cited among the reasons for said choice.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Lagneau |first=Laurent |date=2023-03-02 |title=Le Danemark a confirmé l'achat d'obusiers ATMOS auprès d'Elbit Systems pour remplacer ses CAESAr |url=https://www.opex360.com/2023/03/02/le-danemark-a-confirme-lachat-dobusiers-atmos-aupres-delbit-systems-pour-remplacer-ses-caesar/ |access-date=2023-04-14 |website=Zone Militaire |language=fr-FR}}</ref> Denmark's interest in purchasing 8 [[Lynx (multiple rocket launcher)|PULS rocket artillery systems]] from [[Elbit Systems]] as well as the fact that it already operated the [[Cardom]] 120&nbsp;mm [[self-propelled mortar]], which is produced by Soltam as well, had reportedly also favored the acquisition of the ATMOS as it meant having a sole supplier (Israel) for the artillery segment.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Denmark orders ATMOS SPHs and PULS MRLs |url=https://www.janes.com/defence-news/news-detail/denmark-orders-atmos-sphs-and-puls-mrls |website=Janes.com| publisher= Janes Information Services |language=en |access-date=2023-04-14}}</ref>

=== Failed bids ===

* {{flagicon|BRA}} - [[Brazilian Army]]: The CAESAR was offered to the Brazilian Army as part of the "VBCOAP 155mm SR" program for the acquisition of 36 [[self-propelled gun]]s.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Caiafa |first=Roberto |date=2021-07-12 |title=Exército Brasileiro avalia compra de 36 obuseiros autopropulsados de 155 mm |url=https://www.infodefensa.com/texto-diario/mostrar/3056141/exercito-brasileiro-avalia-compra-36-obuseiros-autopropulsados-155-mm |access-date=2022-10-06 |website=Infodefensa |publisher=Grupo Metalia |language=pt-br}}</ref> Among the competitors are the Brazilian project ''"Sistema de Artillería 155mm/52 AP SR Tupã"'' by Avibras Aeroespacial, potentially the [[Artillery Gun Module]] by [[Krauss-Maffei Wegmann|KMW]] (derived from the [[Panzerhaubitze 2000|PzH2000]]) The other, and main competitor is the [[ATMOS 2000]] presented by [[Elbit Systems]]. Elbit is a strong competitor as it has subsidiaries in Brazil ([[Ares Aeroespacial e Defesa|ARES Aerospacial e Defesa]] and [[AEL Sistemas]]) which would guarantee the logistical support and a technology transfer. The ATMOS 2000 won the competition in April 2024.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2024-04-29 |title=VBCOAP 155 SR – ATMOS, o novo "Sniper" da Artilharia do Exército |url=https://tecnodefesa.com.br/vbcoap-155-sr-atmos-o-novo-sniper-da-artilharia-do-exercito/ |access-date=2024-05-01 |website= Tecnodefesa.com.br |language=pt-BR}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Bastos |first=Paulo |date=2024-04-29 |title=36 vehículos blindados ATMOS: el nuevo "Sniper" de la Artillería del Ejército de Brasil |url=https://www.pucara.org/post/36-veh%C3%ADculos-blindados-atmos-el-nuevo-sniper-de-la-artiller%C3%ADa-del-ej%C3%A9rcito-de-brasil |access-date=2024-05-01 |website=Pucará Defensa |language=es}}</ref>
*{{flagicon|COL}} - [[National Army of Colombia]]: The CAESAR was one of the competitors of the program ''"Soberana"'', intended to provide the future 155&nbsp;mm artillery system. The other competitors were the ATMOS 2000 and the Turkish Yavuz SPh 6×6 by [[Mechanical and Chemical Industry Corporation|MKE]]. On 1 January 2023, Indodefensa announced that the Colombian Army favored the French system and that the government was about to notify the contract for the CAESAR 6x6 to Nexter for US$101.7 million.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Saumeth |first=Erich |date=2023-01-01 |title=Colombia adquiere a Nexter el sistema de artillería Caesar 6x6 por 101 millones de dólares |url=https://www.infodefensa.com/texto-diario/mostrar/4125251/colombia-colombia-adquiere-sistema-artilleria-auto-propulsada-caesar |access-date=2023-04-14 |website=Infodefensa |publisher=Grupo Metalia |language=es}}</ref> However, on 3 January 2023, Colombia announced the order of 18 ATMOS 2000 for US$101.7 million.<ref name="Higuera">{{Cite web |last=Higuera |first=José |date=2023-01-06 |title=Colombia picks Elbit's Atmos howitzer over Nexter's Caesar |url=https://www.defensenews.com/land/2023/01/06/colombia-picks-elbits-atmos-howitzer-over-nexters-caesar/ |access-date=2023-04-14 |website=Defense News |language=en}}</ref> It was reported the value of the CAESAR contract notified by Nexter exceeded the budget allocated to the program, leading to the negotiations falling through and Colombia choosing the ATMOS instead.<ref name="Higuera"/><ref>{{Cite web |last=Lagneau |first=Laurent |date=2023-01-03 |title=À la dernière minute, la Colombie aurait renoncé au CAESAr français… au profit de l'ATMOS israélien |url=https://www.opex360.com/2023/01/03/a-la-derniere-minute-la-colombie-aurait-renonce-au-caesar-francais-au-profit-de-latmos-israelien/ |access-date=2023-07-26 |website=Zone Militaire |language=fr-FR}}</ref>
* {{flagicon|NOR}} - [[Norwegian Army]]: In January 2016, Norway had shortlisted CAESAR, the K9 Thunder, the PzH 2000 and a modernised version of the M109 Paladin proposed by Switzerland's RUAG to replace the 18 M109A3GN self-propelled guns in service with the Norwegian Armed forces. The K9 was selected for purchase in December 2017.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Lagneau |first=Laurent |date=2017-12-22 |title=La Norvège choisit le système sud-coréen K9 Thunder pour moderniser son artillerie |url=https://www.opex360.com/2017/12/22/norvege-choisit-systeme-sud-coreen-k9-thunder-moderniser-artillerie/ |access-date=2023-07-26 |website=Zone Militaire |language=fr-FR}}</ref>
* {{flagicon|UK}} - [[British Army]]: The army was looking for a replacement for the [[AS-90]] tracked self-propelled howitzers by 2032 (under a project named Mobile Fire Platform). All types of self-propelled howitzers were being considered. 116 units are to be acquired.<ref name="UK eyes US mobile howitzer shoot-off">{{Cite web |last=Lye |first=Harry |date=2021-05-19 |title=UK eyes US mobile howitzer shoot-off to inform Mobile Fires Platform |url=https://www.army-technology.com/news/uk-eyes-us-mobile-howitzer-shoot-off-to-inform-mobile-fires-platform/ |access-date=2023-04-15 |website=Army Technology |language=en-US}}</ref> The UK had already acquired 14 [[Archer Artillery System]]s as a short-term solution to replace the 30 AS-90 transferred to Ukraine. The 8×8 Archer variant is offered as part of the MFP program.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Thomas |first=Richard |date=2023-03-16 |title=UK goes for the Archer 155mm as interim artillery solution |url=https://www.army-technology.com/news/uk-goes-for-the-archer-155mm-as-interim-artillery-solution/ |access-date=2023-04-15 |website=Army Technology |language=en-US}}</ref> Other prominent bidders included [[Hanwha Aerospace]] with its [[K9 Thunder]]<ref>{{Cite web |last=Bisht |first=Inder Singh |date=2022-03-22 |title=Lockheed Martin Joins UK K9 Thunder Howitzer Program |url=https://www.thedefensepost.com/2022/03/22/lockheed-uk-k9-thunder-howitzer/ |access-date=2023-04-15 |website=The Defense Post |language=en-US}}</ref> and [[KNDS]] (Nexter and [[Krauss-Maffei Wegmann|KMW]]) with the 8×8 CAESAR and the [[RCH 155]]. In April 2024, the United Kingdom selected the RCH 155.<ref>{{cite press release |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=23 April 2024 |title=PM: UK and Germany open 'new chapter' in defence partnership |url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/pm-uk-and-germany-open-new-chapter-in-defence-partnership |access-date=24 April 2024 |publisher=[[Prime Minister's Office (United Kingdom)|Prime Minister's Office]] |location=London, United Kingdom}}</ref>

=== Evaluation only ===
* {{flagicon|IND}} - [[Indian Army]]: The army is looking to modernise its artillery. The [[Field Artillery Rationalisation Plan]] defined in 2021 the way to be followed, focusing on the Made in India. The Indian Army is expecting<ref>{{Cite web |title=Indian Artillery – Current and Future Status |url=https://www.spslandforces.com/story/?id=479&h=Indian-Artillery-andndash;-Current-and-Future-Status |website= spslandforces.com |language= en |access-date=2023-04-15}}</ref> 814 truck-mounted guns (MGS program = mounted gun system). An [[Request for information|RFI]] was issued on 3 April 2021, with the intent to acquire a truck-mounted howitzer capable of being deployed in deserts, high altitude and mountainous terrains.<ref>{{Cite web |title=DRDO tests mounted gun system |url=https://www.janes.com/defence-news/news-detail/drdo-tests-mounted-gun-system |website=Janes.com| publisher= Janes Information Services |language=en |access-date=2023-04-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| last= Shukla| first= Ajai| date= 19 October 2022| title= MGS, Light Tank, WhaP: DRDO presents 3 'Make in India' successes at DefExpo| url= https://www.business-standard.com/article/economy-policy/mgs-light-tank-whap-drdo-presents-3-make-in-india-successes-at-defexpo-122101901283_1.html| work= [[Business Standard]]| location= New Delhi, India| publisher= Business Standard Ltd| access-date= 19 June 2024}}</ref> CAESAR was offered in 2014 as part of a collaboration between [[Nexter Systems]] and [[Larsen & Toubro]]. The system is mounted on an [[Ashok Leyland Stallion#Super Stallion|Ashok Leyland Super Stallion 6×6]]. India was initially interested in an MGS, 200 that would be ordered off-shelf, and later 614 manufactured locally.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Indigenously made truck-mounted heavy artillery gun will meet long pending requirement |url= https://forceindia.net/feature-report/shoot-and-scoot/| website= forceindia.net| publisher= |language=en-US |access-date=2024-08-25}}</ref> The tender initially opened to foreign bidders was, however, scrapped for the sake of the [[Make in India]] initiative, favoring local designs.
* {{flagicon|USA}} - [[United States Army]] & [[United States Marine Corps]]: The Army was interested in a mobile platform. Some "Mobile Howitzer Trials and Shoot-Off" had been occurring in 2021.<ref name="UK eyes US mobile howitzer shoot-off" /> The systems tested were the CAESAR, the ATMOS 2000, the [[Archer Artillery System|Archer]] and the [[Nora B-52]]. The Army was very positive with the CAESAR,<ref>{{Cite web |last=Lagneau |first=Laurent |date=2022-01-19 |title=Artillerie : Le CAESAr du français Nexter se distingue aux États-Unis en tirant des obus 'Excalibur' |url=https://www.opex360.com/2022/01/19/artillerie-le-caesar-du-francais-nexter-se-distingue-aux-etats-unis-en-tirant-des-obus-excalibur/ |access-date=2023-04-15 |website=Zone Militaire |language=fr-FR}}</ref> but ultimately did not move forward with acquiring a wheeled howitzer system.<ref>{{cite news|date= 2023-10-09|title= Change of plans: US Army embraces lessons learned from war in Ukraine|work= [[Defense News]]|url= https://www.defensenews.com/land/2023/10/09/change-of-plans-us-army-embraces-lessons-learned-from-war-in-ukraine/ |access-date= 2025-11-12}}</ref>

